"1322","1310":"1310","1288":"1288","about 1334":"about 1334","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Aske, Easby, Yorkshire, England":"Aske, Easby, Yorkshire, England","Aske, Yorksshire, England":"Aske, North Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Aske, Yorkshire, England":"Aske, Easby, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Aske","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Yorkshire and Staffordshire): topographic name from northern Middle English <i>ask</i> ‘ash tree’ (Old Norse <i>askr</i>), or a habitational name from Aske (North Yorkshire). Compare   Ash  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Ash","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>asche</i> ‘ash tree’ (Old English <i>æsc</i>), hence a topographic name for someone living by an ash tree or a habitational name from any of the many places in southern and central England named with this word (Derbyshire, Dorset, Hampshire, Herefordshire, Kent, Surrey, Shropshire, Somerset, and elsewhere).","Americanized form of German   Asch   and   Esch  , the latter ultimately also of Swiss German origin (see   Oesch  ).","Americanized form (translation into English) of French   Dufresne  , with the same meaning as 1 above."]},{"name":"Axe","meanings":["English (West Yorkshire, Lincolnshire): variant of   Aske   with metathesis of /sk/ to /ks/, spelled with an <i>x</i>.","English (Dorset, Somerset): habitational name from Axe Farm in Chardstock (Devon, formerly in Dorset), itself named for the river Axe, which forms part of the south-eastern boundary of Chardstock parish.","Americanized form of German   Axt   or perhaps of some other similar (like-sounding) surname."]}]},{"name":"Roger","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name, <i>Rog(i)er</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, from <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>gār</i>, <i>gēr</i> ‘spear’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain, replacing the native Old English form <i>Hrōðgār</i>. <i>Roger</i> was one of the most popular boys' names throughout the medieval period, but less so after the Reformation, though it has continued in regular use to the present day.  Roger, Count of Sicily  (  <i>c.</i>1031–1101 ), son of Tancred, recovered Sicily from the Arabs. His son, also called Roger, ruled Sicily as king, presiding over a court noted for its splendour and patronage of the arts."],"variants":[{"name":"Rodger","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Roger  , in part from the surname derived from the given name in the Middle Ages."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Roger de Aske was born about 1280, in Aske, Easby, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Hugh de Aske, was 11278 and his mother, Cecilia of England, was 42. He married Christina about 1334. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died in Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"about 1280–":"umbes 1280–Surnud","1280–Male":"1280–Surnud","1284–1335":"1284–1335","1286–Male":"1286–Surnud","1288–Male":"1288–Surnud","1310–Female":"1310–Surnud","1322–1392":"1322–1392","1348–Male":"1348–Surnud","1240–Male":"1240–Surnud","1240–1304":"1240–1304","about 1280":"umbes 1280","1